<h3>Web Portals</h3>
<h4>Badilisha Poetry Exchange</h4>
<p>
  <a href="http://badilishapoetry.com/">http://badilishapoetry.com/</a>
</p>

<p>Badilisha Poetry X-Change is both an online audio archive and Pan-African poetry show delivered in radio format. Now the largest online collective of African poets on the planet, Badilisha has showcased and archived over 500 Pan-African poets from 28 different countries. It reflects the myriad of rhythms and rhymes, voices, perspectives and aspirations from all corners of the globe.</p>


<h4>Poetry International Rotterdam</h4>
<p>
  <a href="https://www.poetryinternational.org/pi/countries/en/tile">https://www.poetryinternational.org/pi/countries/en/tile</a>
</p>

<p>For 50 years Poetry International has featured poets from all around the world including many African countries. Their archive contains bios, occasional individual poems in English the translation and Dutch translation of poets who have performed at festival over the years. In some cases, they have done special featured events on African poetry which have added to the list of poets even though they have not attended the festival. Their Festival Archive dates back to 1970 and lists all the visiting poets by country.</p>



<h4>Poetry Translation Center</h4>
<p>
  <a href="https://www.poetrytranslation.org/about">https://www.poetrytranslation.org/about</a>
</p>

<p>The center was established in 2004 and devotes its work to updating this free archival site of poetry translated into English primarily from Latin America, the Middle East, Asia and Africa. The following African countries are represented. This is not a comprehensive e source of African poetry as each entry per country is relatively modest. Nonetheless it is an important source to identify non-English poets from African whose work may have been translated into English. The following countries are listed:</p>

